Excellent soup. I love the squash combo of butternut and acorn. I peeled the squash, but will roast it next time as it was a pain in the a**. And I agree that you should halve or quarter the baguette slices. I did use the sugar, but the soup would be just as good, I'm sure, without it. I also agree that you should use the fresh herbs, not dry herbs. Don't skimp on that.

Rating: 4
I cook a lot of great things, and this soup has definitely qualified as a keeper. I had a couple of techniques that made the raw squash not so bad to peel (Google it and/or use common sense), and I thought it might possibly taste better to actually cook the squash with the herbs rather than roast is seperately. I'd suggest only making this soup if you use the fresh herbs, there's just no comparison to dried thyme and sage. I was actually led here by a variation tha included 1.5 teaspoons of ground cumin and 0.5 teaspoon of dried ginger. I used freshly ground cumin and 1 teaspoon of freshly grated ginger instead. Made the croutons with romano and the herbs since I didn't feel like buying gruyere, and the croutons really add some very worthwhile savoriness, though you could eat the soup quite happily without them. Last thing, I never sautee garlic for 10 minutes. I did the onions maybe for 7 and then added garlic for 3-4 more. For goodness' sake don't burn the garlic and make it bitter. Oh, I used homemade veggie stock rather than chicken, I don't know why to use chicken for a vegetarian recipe except maybe the veggie broth is harder to find. Cheers!

