Rating: 4
It was excellent! As others suggested, I baked the squash rather than peeling and boiling. I cut the squash into large pieces and placed them in a roasting pan with 1/4 inch of water; covered it with foil and baked 20 to 30 minutes in a 400 degree oven. Note: adding oil roasts rather than bakes the squash and changes the flavor as well as adding fat. Also, I suggest adding the stock slowly, so you don't add too much and thin it out. I used 32 oz. of stock.

Rating: 4
I made this as a light side for my family's thanksgiving dinner. It was the hit of the meal. Everyone commented on how much they enjoyed it. If you like winter squash and soup give this one a try!

Rating: 3
Simple, healthy and delicious for a winter night meal. Don't skip the whipping cream and sugar at the end. The soup will taste flat without the creaminess, and the sugar (try brown sugar) brings out the natural sweetness of the squash. These two ingredients make the flavor pop! Like other reviewers, I'd also recommend baking the squash first with olive oil, salt & pepper (I did 350 degrees for 30-40 min). This made the entire process very simple. The flesh came right off and there's no need to add more salt & pepper later on. I did not have fresh thyme or sage, nor herbs de provence, so I used Italian seasoning instead. It still tasted wonderful. I will have to try fresh herbs next time. While waiting for the squash to bake, I washed the seeds and mixed them with a drizzle of olive oil, sprinkled sea salt on top and put it in the oven with the squash. After 5-10 min it's a tasty salty snack. Both made the house smell wonderful! This is a good, solid recipe. I plan on making it again and adding some twists (I found a recipe with a five- spice creme fraiche and candied ginger topping).

