I made this recipe as the first course of a french-themed New Years Eve dinner and it was well received. I topped with lardons and toasted hazelnut crumbs instead of the crouton, and people loved the flavors. I didn't use the full amount of broth - just over 2 cans - and it had a creamy wintery consistency that seemed just right. I am able to find the squash pre-cut in my grocery store which cuts down drastically on the work involved to make this. I will definitely make it again.

Rating: 4
We started preparing this soup in 1996 when the recipe was first published. It has been a staple of any winter feast since, and an absolute MUST for Christmas dinner. I love telling friends that I am making squash soup...it could be a whole segment on a reality TV show... watching their faces go from scrunching up like a 2-year-old who doesn't want to eat their veggies... to the inevitable response of, "May I have some more please?" and/or "May I have the recipe?". I do have three hints for you... #1) Dont skip the croutons! While the soup can absolutely stand on its own merits, the croutons take it to an entirely different level. #2)Yes, the squash is difficult to cut up... simply call the grocery store before you arrive and ask them to have it peeled and cut into one inch cubes for you, (then you don't have the hassle of cutting it up AND you aren't paying per pound for the skins and seeds you are most likely going to throw away) and finally #3) encourage your guests to lightly salt/pepper the soup in their own bowl when it is served, a tiny bit of salt brings out the sweetness and distinct flavors. Enjoy this one... it is a keeper (and you can ask my 16 year old son, who just loves this soup)!

