Rating: 4
I made this soup for the first course at Thanksgiving dinner and it was a hit. I used acorn and butternut squash. Incorporating the suggestion of other reviewers, the night before Thanksgiving I cut the squash lengthwise in half, scooped out the seeds and roasted them at 350 degrees F for an hour on a foil-lined baking sheet coated with olive oil. Then I finished the soup the morning of Thanksgiving. I had read a comment suggesting the soup was too thin, so I started with a quart of the chicken broth, then once the squash and broth were pureed, added more broth to the pot to bring the soup to the consistency I wanted. I also used a light touch on the garlic and the herbs, and found the soup needed a little salt. The croutons were the crown jewel and were quick and easy -- important when you've got the rest of the Thanksgiving three- ring circus meal prep going on. The soup tastes rich and elegant but is deceptively simple to make. And it was healthier than most of the other dishes I served, too; the quarter cup each of butter and cream were split among 10 people.

