Rating: 4
Another big fan of this recipe, which is so filling we serve it as a main course, along with a light salad. This far surpasses any of the other recipes I've tried for squash, pumpkin or sweet potato soups. So much has already been written, so I'll just add a few additional comments: 1) DEFINITELY roast the squash, it'll save you hours in peeling time, while adding a lovely carmelized flavor to the soup. 2) Be sure to roast it early enough so that it is cool to handle for scooping out the flesh. 3) Use fresh herbs, and be sure to sprinkle some on the croutons. 4) I didn't find the garlic to be overwhelming at all, but I did like it better when I roasted the garlic under the squash (as someone else suggested) rather than sauted it with the onions. 5) I don't have a wand, so I just used my food processer...wasn't a problem at all, did it in two batches, I just poured half of it in a bowl first then processed the other half.

