Made this today for our restaurant's Valentine's Dinner Menu. I followed the ingredients exactly, however as others have suggested, to save time and work. Simply steam the squash in your oven. No need to peel and cut it up. Also, instead of pureeing it in batches, simply use a wand. Very easy and simple to make, with a beautiful presentation. I also made the croutons the day before, except for adding the cheese under the broiler.

Rating: 4
Yum! I've been searching for a squash soup that rivals that of my favorite French bistro in NYC - and this one comes awfully close. I made a few changes to suit my taste and it came out fantastic. Instead of acorn squash I used all butternut. I left out the thyme and added some traditional squash seasonings (a dash here and there) like nutmeg, cloves, cinnamon and a few tsp of sugar. The sugar really brings out the flavor of the squash without making the soup sweet. The spices added a subtle flavor and the overall soup was still very savory. I also increased the broth to maintain a velvety texture since I had so much squash. Other than that it was the norm - salt and pepper to taste, a touch of cream to finish and it was amazing! Oh yes, I almost forgot - invest in a hand blender . . . so much easier than using a food processor and it gets the whole thing done at once.

Rating: 4
Outstanding! and that's with some shortcuts I took. Instead of boiling the squashes called for, I sauteed the onion and garlic, added the broth, put it into a large pot, and added 4 packages frozen pureed winter squash (about 10oz by weight each) and one can of pureed pumpkin (not pumpkin pie filling). I added two Tablespoons of sugar (more than the recipe said) but sweetness was still very subtle. I also added 1/4 tsp ground ginger which didn't really register--I might try more another time, or just leave it out. Finally, I added 1/2 cup creme fraiche rather than the 1/4 c whipping cream because I like the slightly sour flavor of creme fraiche. (For homemade creme fraiche, combine 1 cup whipping cream with 1 cup sour cream. Let stand 2 hours in a warmish place, then refrigerate until thickened. Use the leftover on sugared fruit, with baked applies or chocolate desserts, etc) I bought store-made parmesan and garlic flavored croutons at my local gourmet store. The croutons do add flavor to the soup. Again, with all this cheating the soup was excellent; with all the original pains taken I'm sure it's even better.

Rating: 4
