I followed the advice re: roasting the squash w/garlic and sage. Used all acorn squash as that was on sale that day. Putting it through a blender lends an exceptional quality ... the croutons, though, absolutely MAKE this soup an EVENT.

Rating: 4
This is so delicious! I followed the recipe exactly and would do so again. I suspect that roasting the squash alters the beautiful golden yellow color that is such an appealing feature of this soup. It's kind of a pain to peel the squash, but the extra work is probably worth the trouble. The gruyere toasts are a great accompaniment.

Rating: 3
A wonderful winter soup. I made a few changes though.... Like several other people I also roasted the squash -- much easier than peeling and chopping. I cut the squash in half put 3 garlic cloves in each cavity, poured olive oil over each half and sprinkled with some of the sage and thyme and salt and pepper. I covered the squash with foil and roasted at 400 for about 1 hour. Once done it was very easy to scoop out with a spoon. I used half bacon fat and half butter to saute the onions. I did not bother to puree the soup. The roasted squash is already pretty much a puree. I used a potato masher to smooth it a little more. I like texture to my soup, although I might puree if making it for guests. A keeper!

Rating: 4
Awesome!! I look forward to the fall now, not just for the colour of the leaves, but for the squash!

